{"text": "states on each wire ky.13 In doing so, we obtain the polarizations Px(ky) \u2208[0, 1) of the 1D exponentially-localized\n\norbitals. Within the Modern Theory of Polarization, these polarizations are related to the eigenvalues of the Wilson\n\nloop along each wire ky. In addition, we demand that the basis transforms in a prescribed way under the anti-unitary\n\nsymmetry I, namely the following purely off-diagonal form:\n\nOI(k) = \u27e8v(k) \u02c6I v(k)\u27e9= e\u22122\u03c0i(P +(ky)+P \u2212(ky))kx/Nxsx\u03c3x,\n\n(B18)\n\nwhere sx and \u03c3x are the usual Pauli matrix (in the spin and Wannier label), and the 1D Hybrid Wannier states are\n\ngiven by vls(k)\u27e9= \u02c6\u03c6\u2020\n\nls(k) 0\u27e9=\n\nX\n\n\u03c3,l\n\n\u02c6\u03c8\u2020\n\n\u03c3ls(k) 0\u27e9v\u03c3l,l(k).\n\n(B19)\n\nSince I anti-commutes with the position operator \u02c6I\u02c6r = \u2212\u02c6r\u02c6I, then the two polarizations are opposite (modulo unity),\n\nwhich implies that P +(ky) + P \u2212(ky) takes an integer value on each wire.\n\nHaving chosen the above off-diagonal action of I, we guarantee that our basis has several important and convenient\n\nproperties. Most crucially, the basis is a layer-polarized basis. As defined in the main text, such a basis (i) diagonalizes\n\nthe action of the (projected) layer operator\n\nOlz(k) = \u27e8v(k) \u02c6lz v(k)\u27e9= v\u2020(k)lzv(k),\n\n(B20)\n\nwith (ii) eigenvalues \u03bbl(k) that take a constant sign across the Brillouin zone. To see this, we recall that \u02c6I \u02c6\u03c8\u2020(k)\u02c6I =\n\n\u02c6\u03c8\u2020(k)lxsx, and remark that Eq. (B18) is then equivalent to the constraint\n\nv\u2020(k)lxv\u2217(k) = ei\u03b3(k)\u03c3x,\n\n(B21)\n\n13 Due to the finite circumference Ly of the cylinder, ky takes Ly-many quantized values. We therefore refer to each constant-ky slice as\n\na \u201cwire,\u201d along which kx is effectively continuous.\n\n35\n\n(a)\n\n(b)\n\n(c)\n\n(d)\n\n\u2212\u03c0/4\n\n0\n\n\u03c0/4\n\nkx\n\n\u2212\u03